# DS Storybook Testing

Use this rule when writing Storybook stories with interaction and a11y tests for Design System components.

## Location & imports

Stories live in `apps/storybook/src/stories/[name]/[name].stories.tsx`, separate from component source in `packages/ui`.

```ts
import type { Meta, StoryObj } from "@storybook/react-vite";
import { expect, userEvent, within } from "storybook/test";
import { Button } from "@ds-12/ui/button";
import { StoryCaption, StorySectionTitle } from "../../lib/story-presentation.tsx";
```

Use `@ds-12/ui/[name]` subpath imports. Storybook resolves these via the `@ds-12/ui` alias in `apps/storybook/vite.config.ts` (no per-component alias needed).

## Setup (already configured)

Storybook 10 is configured in `apps/storybook/.storybook/main.ts`:

```ts
addons: [
  "@chromatic-com/storybook",
  "@storybook/addon-a11y",
  "@storybook/addon-docs",
  "@storybook/addon-mcp",
],
framework: "@storybook/react-vite",
```

Interaction tests use `play` functions with utilities from `storybook/test` (Storybook 10), not `@storybook/test`. Run them manually from the Storybook UI (Interactions panel); CI uses Chromatic for visual regression only.

A11y is enabled globally in `apps/storybook/.storybook/preview.tsx` with `a11y.test: "todo"`.

## Story file structure

Every component story file should include:

1. **Visual stories** — `Default`, per-variant/per-size stories, and an `AllVariants` showcase (existing convention)
2. **Interaction stories** — dedicated stories with `play` functions for behavior and a11y

Use `tags: ["autodocs"]` and `satisfies Meta<typeof Component>` on the meta object.

For stateful components, wrap in a local helper (see `pagination.stories.tsx`):

```ts
function InteractivePagination({ page: initialPage = 1, ...props }: PaginationProps) {
  const [page, setPage] = useState(initialPage);
  return <Pagination {...props} page={page} onPageChange={setPage} />;
}
```

## Required interaction stories

Apply the stories below based on component type. Skip stories that do not apply (e.g. skip `Disabled` for non-interactive components like Divider or Skeleton).

### Interactive controls (Button, Chip, Input, Pagination, …)

#### 1. KeyboardFocus

Tab into the component and assert focus is received:

```ts
export const KeyboardFocus: Story = {
  args: { children: "Button" },
  play: async ({ canvasElement }) => {
    const canvas = within(canvasElement);
    const el = canvas.getByRole("button", { name: /button/i });

    await userEvent.tab();
    await expect(el).toHaveFocus();
  },
};
```

#### 2. FocusVisible

Keyboard focus triggers `data-focus-visible` (Base UI convention):

```ts
export const FocusVisible: Story = {
  args: { children: "Button" },
  play: async ({ canvasElement }) => {
    const canvas = within(canvasElement);
    const el = canvas.getByRole("button", { name: /button/i });

    await userEvent.tab();
    await expect(el).toHaveAttribute("data-focus-visible");
  },
};
```

#### 3. MouseClickNoFocusVisible

Mouse click does NOT trigger focus-visible:

```ts
export const MouseClickNoFocusVisible: Story = {
  args: { children: "Button" },
  play: async ({ canvasElement }) => {
    const canvas = within(canvasElement);
    const el = canvas.getByRole("button", { name: /button/i });

    await userEvent.click(el);
    await expect(el).not.toHaveAttribute("data-focus-visible");
  },
};
```

#### 4. Disabled

Base UI interactive components use `disabled` prop; assert the rendered disabled state. Disabled controls must remain keyboard-focusable:

```ts
export const DisabledInteraction: Story = {
  args: { disabled: true, children: "Button" },
  play: async ({ canvasElement }) => {
    const canvas = within(canvasElement);
    const el = canvas.getByRole("button", { name: /button/i });

    await expect(el).toHaveAttribute("aria-disabled", "true");
    await userEvent.tab();
    await expect(el).toHaveFocus();
  },
};
```

Use a distinct story name (`DisabledInteraction`) when a visual-only `Disabled` story already exists.

#### 5. AccessibleName

Component must have an accessible name resolvable by `getByRole`:

```ts
export const AccessibleName: Story = {
  args: { children: "Button" },
  play: async ({ canvasElement }) => {
    const canvas = within(canvasElement);

    await expect(
      canvas.getByRole("button", { name: /button/i }),
    ).toBeInTheDocument();
  },
};
```

Icon-only buttons need an explicit `aria-label` in args:

```ts
export const AccessibleName: Story = {
  args: { variant: "icon", "aria-label": "Add" },
  play: async ({ canvasElement }) => {
    const canvas = within(canvasElement);
    await expect(canvas.getByRole("button", { name: /add/i })).toBeInTheDocument();
  },
};
```

### Toggle components (Chip)

Chip uses Base UI `Button` with `aria-pressed`. Confirm the role before writing queries:

```ts
export const Toggle: Story = {
  args: { children: "Label", active: false },
  play: async ({ canvasElement }) => {
    const canvas = within(canvasElement);
    const chip = canvas.getByRole("button", { name: /label/i });

    await expect(chip).toHaveAttribute("aria-pressed", "false");
    await userEvent.click(chip);
    await expect(chip).toHaveAttribute("aria-pressed", "true");
  },
};
```

For checkbox-pattern toggles, use `getByRole("checkbox")` and `toBeChecked()` instead.

### Non-interactive / presentational components (Divider, Skeleton, Typography, Badge)

Skip focus/disabled stories. Assert semantic structure instead:

```ts
// Skeleton — status role + accessible name
export const AccessibleName: Story = {
  args: { "aria-label": "Loading" },
  play: async ({ canvasElement }) => {
    const canvas = within(canvasElement);
    await expect(canvas.getByRole("status", { name: /loading/i })).toBeInTheDocument();
  },
};

// Divider — separator role
export const AccessibleStructure: Story = {
  play: async ({ canvasElement }) => {
    const canvas = within(canvasElement);
    await expect(canvas.getByRole("separator")).toBeInTheDocument();
  },
};
```

### Composite components (InputField, TextareaField)

Test the primary interactive element inside the field wrapper:

```ts
export const KeyboardFocus: Story = {
  play: async ({ canvasElement }) => {
    const canvas = within(canvasElement);
    const input = canvas.getByRole("textbox", { name: /label/i });

    await userEvent.tab();
    await expect(input).toHaveFocus();
  },
};
```

## Rules

- Use `getByRole` with `name` option — never query by class or test-id unless no semantic role exists
- Do NOT assert CSS class names — assert behavior and ARIA attributes
- Do NOT assert visual styles (color, spacing) — that belongs to visual regression (Chromatic)
- Always confirm the component's rendered role before writing `getByRole` queries
- Keep visual stories and interaction stories in the same file; interaction stories use `play`, visual stories do not
- Run interaction tests from the Storybook UI (Interactions panel)
